Slide Flick is a frame-by-frame custom animation engine built purely in VBA for Microsoft PowerPoint. It bypasses native PowerPoint animations, driving complex layout transformations on a single slide using a high-performance timeline architecture.Target Frame Rate: Up to 24 FPS.Target Scale: Seamlessly manages up to 500+ shapes across 720+ frames (30-second sequences).Cross-Platform: Native compatibility with Windows PC and macOS.🏗️ Core Architecture & Data PipelineTo maximize performance within VBA's single-threaded environment, Slide Flick uses a Sparse Keyframe Registry Pattern. Instead of polling every shape or checking monolithic arrays on every frame tick, the engine isolates data tracking at both the Property level and the Shape level.1. Global Shape Registries (The Property Filters)To prevent redundant iterations, shapes are registered only into the specific property pipelines they utilize. A single shape can live in multiple registries if it uses multiple properties.movingShapes (Collection): Only contains Shape IDs that actively change Left, Top, or Rotation.scalingShapes (Collection): Only contains Shape IDs that actively change Width or Height (used for squash/stretch or simulating a Z-axis).switchingShapes (Collection): Only contains Shape IDs tied to visibility toggles (e.g., character blinks or Switch Board phoneme mouth shapes).2. Timeline Object Model (clsAnimatedShape)Every animated shape is backed by an instance of a class module (clsAnimatedShape). Timeline data is stored in native VBA collections using string-based frame keys (e.g., "F1", "F45") to achieve instant O(1) memory lookups during scrubbing.vba' --- clsAnimatedShape Class Attributes ---
Public ShapeID As Long
Public PositionTimeline As Collection   ' Keys: "F1", "F2"... Values: Array(Left, Top, Rotation)
Public ScaleTimeline As Collection      ' Keys: "F1", "F2"... Values: Array(Width, Height)
Public VisibilityTimeline As Collection ' Keys: "F1", "F2"... Values: Boolean
Use code with caution.3. Data PersistenceStorage Mechanism: Serialization via an explicit XML schema.Implementation: Data is compiled into a single XML block and safely embedded directly into the presentation file using native CustomXMLParts. This ensures the animation data persists, transfers, and saves seamlessly with the .pptx file.⚡ Playback & Scrubbing OptimizationScrubbing (Editing Mode): When a user drags the timeline indicator to a specific frame (e.g., jumping from Frame 5 to Frame 3), the engine queries the master shape registries, checks the exact string key for that frame, and updates the canvas instantly.Playback (Presentation Mode): Execution relies on listening to slideshow transition events and calling SlideShowView.GotoSlide.No Multi-Data Blending: If a shape has no entry for a specific frame key, the engine uses On Error Resume Next to safely skip it instantly, wasting zero CPU cycles on un-animated shapes.🍏 Cross-Platform Workarounds (Mac Compatibility)Because Slide Flick runs purely in VBA, it completely avoids Windows-only dependencies like Scripting.Dictionary or Win32 API calls (QueryPerformanceCounter/Sleep).1. The Sandbox File IO Export WorkaroundMac App Sandboxing blocks standard sequential file writing (like exporting several hundred frames to a folder via Shape.Export), triggering endless "Grant Permission" prompts or Error 70.The Slide Flick Solution: When exporting an image sequence on macOS, Slide Flick automatically duplicates the active slide, builds a temporary 720-slide sequential presentation, and pauses to prompt the user to use PowerPoint's native, sandboxed menu path: File > Export > Save as Image Sequence. The temporary file is discarded immediately afterward.2. Copy/Paste Stability & The Zero FrameID Isolation: The engine tracks shapes strictly by their unique PowerPoint IDs. Copy-pasting (CTRL+C / CTRL+V) or duplicating a shape intentionally strips previous animation data.Initialization: When a new shape is recorded for the first time, it is initialized with a Zero Frame data point mapping its baseline properties. Users can override this zero-frame baseline via a dedicated UI button (e.g., starting an asset off-canvas).🚀 Next Phase Implementation Goals (In 2 Months)The Switch Board Feature: System for handling character rigging visibility trees (swapping grouped child components like mouths and eyes cleanly via IDs).Interpolation Engine: Establishing the mathematical tracking for tweening between isolated keyframes during playback.


