there are 2 edge cases that will push this limit.
1: Me. I will push that limit but I know I can just make another presentation and continue where I left off.
2: the inexperienced animator / powerpoint user. example . They animate a character walking. They move the "background" that has 200 shapes. Each shape is recorded for every frame. They should have grouped the shapes behind the character then moved that group along with the shapes in front of the character to create the overlap. Inexperienced people will not understand this and may indeed cause the "program" to run sluggish. 

I see that being the main case here. As the slide flick community is built, best practices will be discussed and honestly the group might be really small. If I am being honest. This add-in is for me. I know how it works. I have a 2003 version that uses nothing but tags. I want to make it work with a newer version so the objects make sense. 

The users who pick this up will probably understand that we need to be kind to it to get it to work. Its a niche tool that is for people who like to draw stuff in PowerPoint and now want to animate it frame by frame. Yeah that audience is small. 
I think we will be ok and I dont think my comp will blow up using this. 
